18 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 37A O.S. 2021, Section 2-103, as
19 amended by Section 5, Chapter 338, O.S.L. 2023 (37A O.S. Supp. 2025,
20 Section 2-103), is amended to read as follows:
21 Section 2-103. A. A distiller license shall authorize the
22 holder thereof:
23 1. To manufacture, bottle, package and store spirits on
24 licensed premises;
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB1946 SFLR Page 8
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 2. To sell spirits in this state to licensed wholesalers and
2 manufacturers only;
3 3. To sell spirits out of this state to qualified persons; to
4 purchase from licensed distillers and rectifiers in this state, and
5 import spirits from without this state for manufacturing purposes in
6 accordance with federal laws and regulations;
7 4. To serve free samples of spirits produced only by the
8 licensee to visitors twenty-one (21) years of age and older. For
9 purposes of this section, no visitor may sample more than a total of
10 three (3) fluid ounces of spirits per day. The distiller shall
11 restrict the distribution and consumption of spirits samples to an
12 area within the licensed premises designated by the distiller. A
13 current floor plan that includes the designated sampling area shall
14 be on file with the ABLE Commission. No visitor under twenty-one
15 (21) years of age shall be permitted to enter the designated
16 sampling area when samples are being distributed and consumed.
17 Samples of spirits served by a distiller under this section shall
18 not be considered a sale of spirits within the meaning of Article
19 XXVIII-A of the Oklahoma Constitution or Section 1-103 of this
20 title; provided, such samples of spirits shall be considered removed
21 or withdrawn from the distillery for use or consumption within the
22 meaning of Section 5-110 of this title for excise tax determination
23 and reporting requirements;
24
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB1946 SFLR Page 9
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 5. To sell spirits produced by the licensee for either on-
2 premises or off-premises consumption to consumers on the licensed
3 distillery premises or in an area controlled by the licensee located
4 contiguous to the licensed distillery premises and at one (1)
5 location locations controlled by the licensee located in the same
6 county state as the licensed distillery premises but not contiguous
7 to the licensed distillery premises. Spirits offered for sale by
8 the Oklahoma licensed distiller will have been sold to and shipped
9 to an Oklahoma licensed wine and spirits wholesaler and then made
10 available for purchase by the Oklahoma licensed distiller for sale;
11 and
12 6. To sell spirits and sample spirits at public events such as
13 trade shows or festivals. Products offered for sale by the Oklahoma
14 licensed distiller will have been sold to and shipped to an Oklahoma
15 licensed wine and spirits wholesaler and then made available for
16 purchase by the Oklahoma licensed distiller. Spirits offered for
17 on-premises consumption shall be in an area controlled by the
18 distillery and shall be considered the distillery premises.
19 B. Spirits sold pursuant to paragraphs 5 and 6 of subsection A
20 of this section shall not exceed fifteen thousand (15,000) gallons
21 per calendar year in combination.
22 C. Spirits sold pursuant to paragraphs 5 and 6 of subsection A
23 of this section shall be a final sale. Licensed distillers may
24 offer for sale non-alcoholic nonalcoholic substances which may be
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB1946 SFLR Page 10
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 adde d to spirits by the consumer after final sale. Substances used
2 for on-premises consumption shall be non-alcoholic nonalcoholic in
3 nature and shall not be considered part of the manufacturing
4 process. Spirits mixed with nonalcoholic substances or spirits
5 produced by the distiller and sold through a distributor in this
6 state shall not be considered a cocktail as defined by Section 1-103
7 of this title.
8 SECTION 3. AMENDATORY 37A O.S. 2021, Section 2-107, is
9 amended to read as follows:
10 Section 2-107. A. A wine and spirits wholesaler license shall
11 authorize the holder thereof:
12 1. To purchase and import into this state spirits and wines
13 from persons authorized to sell same who are the holders of a
14 manufacturer or nonresident seller license, and their agents who are
15 the holders of manufacturer’s agent licenses;
16 2. To purchase spirits and wines from licensed distillers,
17 rectifiers and winemakers in this state;
18 3. To purchase spirits and wines from licensed wholesalers, to
19 the extent set forth in subsections B and C of this section;
20 4. To sell in retail containers in this state to retailers,
21 mixed beverage, caterer, special event, public event, hotel beverage
22 or airline/railroad beverage licensees, spirits and wines which have
23 been received and unloaded at the bonded warehouse facilities of the
24 wholesaler before such sale;
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB1946 SFLR Page 11
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 5. To sell to licensed wholesalers, to the extent set forth in
2 subsections B and C of this section, spirits and wines which have
3 been received and unloaded at the bonded warehouse facilities of the
4 wholesaler before such sale;
5 6. To sell spirits and wines out of this state to qualified
6 persons; and
7 7. To sell to licensed distillers spirits that were
8 manufactured by that distiller and which have been received and
9 unloaded at a bonded warehouse facility of a wholesaler before such
10 sale; and
11 8. To sell to a licensed distiller spirits that were
12 manufactured by such distiller on a price not to exceed a twelve-
13 percent markup above the free-on-board price and state excise taxes.
14 Provided, however, sales of spirits and wine in containers with
15 a capacity of less than one-twentieth (1/20) gallon by a holder of a
16 wholesaler license shall be in full case lots and in the original
17 unbroken case. Wholesalers shall be authorized to place such signs
18 outside their place of business as are required by Acts of Congress
19 and by such laws and regulations promulgated under such Acts.
20 B. A wholesaler may sell spirits and wine to other wholesalers
21 or purchase spirits and wines from other wholesalers without
22 complying with subsection A of this section in the case of the sale,
23 purchase or other transfer or acquisition of the entire business of
24 a wholesaler including the inventory of spirits and wine.
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB1946 SFLR Page 12
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 C. A wholesaler license shall authorize the holder thereof to:
2 1. Maintain not more than three (3) self-owned or leased and
3 self-operated bonded warehouses within this state. All invoices
4 shall be stored at the principal place of business for which the
5 wholesaler license was granted; and
6 2. Accept as payment cash, personal check, cashier’s check,
